tv_ratings <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vaiseys/dav-course/main/Data/tv_ratings.csv")
tv_long <- tv_ratings |>
  group_by(title) |>
  summarise(num_seasons = n()) |>
  ungroup() |>
  left_join(tv_ratings, by = "title") 

tv_long <- tv_long |>
  filter(num_seasons >= 5)
tv_ratings_all_seasons <- tv_long %>%
  group_by(title)
ggplot(data = tv_ratings_all_seasons,
             aes(x = date,
                 group = title,
                 y = av_rating)) +
  geom_line()

As the years go on, there are more shows around 2015.

Question 2

ggplot(data = tv_ratings_all_seasons,

Drama,crime,mystery, Action,Adventure,Drama, and Drama, Romance tend to last longer. The ratings don’t change much throughout the seasons. Looking at the chart, you can see that the show “Are You Afraid of the Dark” just plummeted recently.

Question 4

comedies_dramas <- tv_ratings %>% 
  mutate(is_comedy = if_else(str_detect(genres, "Comedy"), 
                             1, 
                             0)) %>% # If it contains the word comedy then 1, else 0
  filter(is_comedy == 1 | genres == "Drama") %>% # Keep comedies and dramas
  mutate(genres = if_else(genres == "Drama", # Make it so that we only have those two genres
                          "Drama", 
                          "Comedy"))
ggplot(data = comedies_dramas, 
       aes(x = av_rating, group = genres, color = genres)) +
  geom_density() +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Density")

Unfortunately, your prediction does not hold up; drama ratings are higher than comedies.

Question 5

comedies_dramas <- tv_ratings %>% 
  mutate(is_comedy = if_else(str_detect(genres, "Comedy"), 
                             1, 
                             0)) %>% # If it contains the word comedy then 1, else 0
  filter(is_comedy == 1 | genres == "Drama") %>% # Keep comedies and dramas
  mutate(genres = if_else(genres == "Drama", # Make it so that we only have those two genres
                          "Drama", 
                          "Comedy"))
ggplot(data = comedies_dramas, 
       aes(x = av_rating, group = genres, color = genres)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Density")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Based on the bin sizes, this histogram tells me that many of the dramas and comedies were given a rating between 7 and 9.

comedies_dramas <- tv_ratings %>% 
  mutate(is_comedy = if_else(str_detect(genres, "Comedy"), 
                             1, 
                             0)) %>% # If it contains the word comedy then 1, else 0
  filter(is_comedy == 1 | genres == "Drama") %>% # Keep comedies and dramas
  mutate(genres = if_else(genres == "Drama", # Make it so that we only have those two genres
                          "Drama", 
                          "Comedy"))
ggplot(data = comedies_dramas, 
       aes(x = av_rating, group = genres, color = genres)) +
  geom_freqpoly() +
  labs(x = "Rating", y = "Density")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

After using geom_freqpoly, I notice that compared to the line representing Comedy ratings, the Drama line is quite “squiggly”. After looking at all three plots, I think the histogram is more informative because it allows you to get a better picture of both the density and ratings of the data set.

Question 6

ggplot(data = comedies_dramas,
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, y = share)) +
  geom_bin2d()

From this data, I see that the number of shares is quite low, despite the high ratings. In comparison to a scatter plot, type of plot allows you to see how many people are actually watching these shows, no matter the rating.

ggplot(data = comedies_dramas,
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, y = share)) +
  geom_bin2d(fill = "red")

A drama called ‘Dekalog’ is the outlier that with a rating of ~8.2 with ~27 shares.
